          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Lebanon lays it down</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-22-2.png" alt="Lebanon lays it down" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Lebanon’s President Joseph Aoun has called for Israel to withdraw from southern Lebanon by the January 26 deadline, as stipulated in the November 27 ceasefire agreement. Speaking with UN Secretary-General Antonio Guterres, Aoun criticized Israel’s ongoing violations, including border village destruction and airspace incursions, as contradicting the accord.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The agreement requires Israel to withdraw as the Lebanese army and UNIFIL peacekeepers deploy in the south. Meanwhile, Hezbollah must relocate its forces north of the Litani River and dismantle its southern military infrastructure. Hezbollah leader Naim Qassem warned Israel against testing their patience. In addition to Israel, the new Lebanese government has the Hezbollah situation to reckon with. While Hezbollah remains influential, its recent losses in the war with Israel, <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-22-01-2025-h2-3-strained-alliance" target="_blank">strained alliances</a>, and diminished access to weapons have weakened its position.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
